[[div class="blockquote"]]
Dr. Kuang,

To put it bluntly, approving this was a mistake. 

It's not entirely your fault, however. We simply knew too little about sub-reality and we were too bold in our first foray into it. That thing that crawled out of the breach that opened up when you fired up the machine was a [[[scp-106|nightmare incarnate]]]. The stench of its [*/scp-6500/offset/5 decaying body]... We simply cannot allow for another thing like that to escape into our laboratories. The personnel and monetary losses we suffered are absolutely unnaceptable. I hope you realize this means the end of your project -- and all things related to sub-reality, for that matter.

But cheer up -- Johnson at Engineering tells me your particle accelerators have great military applications, and we could really use the money now that the Foundation is breathing down our necks for handling cleanup duty of that monster you brought into our world. Heard they even assigned old Scranton's son to it. Good on him for making a name for himself; shame that it's outside our labs.

Anyway, chin up, Dr. Kuang. We may have stolen fire, but at least we're not being tied to a rock for an eagle to eat our livers daily. There are still new horizons to map, frontiers to explore, and an entire world of possibilities out there for us to lay claim to. 

For great science!

[[>]]
Regards,
//-- Prometheus Laboratories Archival Department, Res. Sasha Stoker//
[[/>]]
[[/div]]

